ch as Bahrain, the contradiction becomes extreme and even unsustainable. Based on long-term ethnographic fieldwork, Gareth Doherty explores the landscapes of Bahrain, where green represents a plethora of implicit human values and exists in dialectical tension with other culturally and environmentally significant colors and hues. Explicit in his book is the argument that concepts of color and object are mutually defining and thus a discussion about green becomes a discussion about the creation of space and place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aColorsxSocial aspectszBahrain. 0aGreenxSocial aspectszBahrain. 0aGreenbeltszBahrain. 0aUrban landscape architecturezBahrain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aarab gulf states.  aarab.  abahrain landscape.  abahrain social infrastructure.  abahrain.  abahraini landscape.  adate palms.  agreen architecture.  agreen cities.  agreen in the built environment.  agreen landscape.  agreen scenery.  agreenbelts.  agreenery.  alandscape architecture.  amanama greenbelt.  amiddle east.  amiddle eastern landscape architecture.  apersian gulf landscape.  apersian gulf.  athe color green.  aurban environments.  aurban landscape architecture.  aurban landscape.  aurban planning.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052028501940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520960626?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520960626423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520960626/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY